text=:Category: PracticeCategory%0a:Title: Whistling, Phonology, and (some) Physics%0a:Author: david_h%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 04.02.2021 - 10:22%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a%0a#foxbegin 210205-173311-744810#%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a#foxend 210205-173311-744810#%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210317-174431-569140#%0a* [-17.03.2021 - 10:44-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210317-174431-569140#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow do "whistled languages" affect the standard views on phonology?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI once watched a video (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l117wfB0g3o) that introduced a whistled language called kuş dili from Turkey. This then raised a few questions: Does whistling involve a different mechanism from "spoken speech?" Is there a standard to write such a language (does IPA work)? How did such languages develop?%0a%0aIt might be interesting to see whether such languages develop separately from the local spoken language, like how sign languages are independent of the local spoken language.%0a%0aAnother cool discussion is the physics of the sound. Different sound frequencies attenuate faster than others (see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stokes%2527s_law_of_sound_attenuation). As such languages are usually developed to ease communication in mountainous areas, are there some sounds that are not as feasible to use in certain situations?%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
