diff:1612462922:1612462922:=1,43d0%0a%3c :Category: PracticeCategory%0a%3c :Title: Whistling, Phonology, and (some) Physics%0a%3c :Author: david_h%0a%3c :Section: %0a%3c :Completed: 04.02.2021 - 10:22%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c How do "whistled languages" affect the standard views on phonology?%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c I once watched a video (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l117wfB0g3o) that introduced a whistled language called kuş dili from Turkey. This then raised a few questions: Does whistling involve a different mechanism from "spoken speech?" Is there a standard to write such a language (does IPA work)? How did such languages develop?%0a%3c %0a%3c It might be interesting to see whether such languages develop separately from the local spoken language, like how sign languages are independent of the local spoken language.%0a%3c %0a%3c Another cool discussion is the physics of the sound. Different sound frequencies attenuate faster than others (see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stokes%2527s_law_of_sound_attenuation). As such languages are usually developed to ease communication in mountainous areas, are there some sounds that are not as feasible to use in certain situations?%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
